# Nmap: The Basics

**Room:** [TryHackMe – Nmap: The Basics](https://tryhackme.com/room/nmap)
**Status:** Completed

## Summary
Practiced host discovery and port scanning fundamentals — CIDR range
scanning, identifying open TCP ports, and accessing discovered web
services to retrieve flags.

## Key Commands
\`\`\`bash
nmap 192.168.0.1/27          # Scan a CIDR range (32 addresses)
nmap <target-ip>             # Default scan — top 1000 TCP ports
nmap -sV <target-ip>         # Service/version detection
\`\`\`

## Key Takeaways
- A /27 CIDR block covers 32 addresses (network + broadcast included),
  so the scan range runs from `.0` to `.31`
- Found 6 open TCP ports on the target, then identified a listening
  web server and retrieved the flag directly via browser
